00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:27.270
So in February 1989 the
final armored column

00:04:27.270 --> 00:04:30.640
of the limited contingent of
Soviet forces in Afghanistan

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:34.000
as the Soviet occupation
army was called crossed

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.800
over the Friendship bridge
of the Amu Darya River,

00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:38.770
officially ending
the Soviet occupation

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:41.280
of Afghanistan during
the 1980's.

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:44.630
General Gromov was the final
Soviet commander and he got

00:04:44.630 --> 00:04:47.440
down from the last
armored personnel carrier

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:49.980
and turned his back on
Afghanistan and walked out

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:52.790
and was greeted by his son who
gave him a bouquet of flowers.

00:04:52.790 --> 00:04:55.360
That's how the Soviet war ended.

00:04:55.360 --> 00:04:58.500
In December 2014 the Obama
administration thought it was

00:04:58.500 --> 00:05:02.270
ending the war in Afghanistan
although it intended to stay

00:05:02.270 --> 00:05:06.080
and hand off support
in an advisory role

00:05:06.080 --> 00:05:08.250
under operation resolution
support.

00:05:08.250 --> 00:05:11.800
But none the less the United
States at that time thought

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:14.780
that it's combat operations
direct combat operations

00:05:14.780 --> 00:05:17.650
in Afghanistan were ending
so they held a ceremony

00:05:17.650 --> 00:05:22.800
in a gymnasium in the bunkered
and fortified headquarters

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:25.220
of the International
Security Assistance Force

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:27.320
in Afghanistan in Kabul.

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:30.710
And they handed out, they
had some military bands.

00:05:30.710 --> 00:05:33.880
They were -- but they were
very well inside an area

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:36.970
that they sometimes
had experienced

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:38.480
of being rocketed in.

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:41.610
So they handed out kind of
a program for the ceremony

00:05:41.610 --> 00:05:44.670
that included instructions about
how to get down on the floor

00:05:44.670 --> 00:05:46.670
and cover your head in
the event of rocketing.

00:05:46.670 --> 00:05:51.520
So that was how the
U.S. war ended once.

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:54.170
And then a year later
it started again.

00:05:54.170 --> 00:05:56.520
And today as you know
we're still actually

00:05:56.520 --> 00:05:58.880
in direct combat
operations in Afghanistan.

00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:01.040
We're fighting two
wars there one directly

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:05.170
against the Islamic state
al-Qaeda affiliated groups.

00:06:05.170 --> 00:06:09.940
And then another that
advisor and assist war that,

00:06:09.940 --> 00:06:12.880
that we thought we were
moving into in 2014.

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:14.350
So it's been 17 years.

00:06:14.350 --> 00:06:15.860
A lot of frustration.

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:17.850
A lot of sacrifice.

00:06:17.850 --> 00:06:20.590
Hundreds and thousands
of Americans volunteered

00:06:20.590 --> 00:06:24.450
over the course of those
years to serve in Afghanistan.

00:06:24.450 --> 00:06:27.040
More than 2,000 American
soldiers died

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:28.700
as did hundreds of contractors.

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:31.790
More than 20,000 soldiers
suffered injuries.

00:06:31.790 --> 00:06:34.750
The casualties among Afghans and
Pakistani's were even greater.

00:06:34.750 --> 00:06:38.620
The war that, that followed the
end of the American invasion

00:06:38.620 --> 00:06:42.520
in 2001 caused about 140,000
deaths directly by the end

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:45.760
of 2014 according to
estimates by researchers

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:49.870
at Brown University and 10
of thousands more since then.

00:06:49.870 --> 00:06:51.400
And of course Afghans

00:06:51.400 --> 00:06:55.240
and Pakistani's have
suffered the most losses,

00:06:55.240 --> 00:06:57.460
even greater losses.

00:06:57.460 --> 00:07:01.820
So why over so many years
and despite some many efforts

00:07:01.820 --> 00:07:04.750
and strategies has the
United States failed

00:07:04.750 --> 00:07:06.640
to achieve its goals
in Afghanistan?

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:09.250
Has it failed to bank
with the Taliban,

00:07:09.250 --> 00:07:11.250
failed to stabilize the country,

00:07:11.250 --> 00:07:14.240
failed to create a
self-sustaining independent

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:18.040
constitutional republic
or democracy of some sort.

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:19.340
It's a long story.

00:07:19.340 --> 00:07:21.710
It's a complicated story,
but as I say I want to draw

00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:23.760
out a few themes and
tell a few stories

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:25.060
around what I think are some

00:07:25.060 --> 00:07:26.810
of the recurring
problems in the war.

00:07:26.810 --> 00:07:30.700
So the first is the
problem of war aims.

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:32.430
Why are we there?

00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:33.730
Which was a question that was

00:07:33.730 --> 00:07:36.920
of course never really formally
addressed before we invaded

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:39.190
Afghanistan because
the war was a hurried

00:07:39.190 --> 00:07:43.310
and a provisional response to
September 11th attacks designed

00:07:43.310 --> 00:07:47.850
to disrupt al-Qaeda which was
in Afghanistan and had carried

00:07:47.850 --> 00:07:50.590
out the attacks substantially
from there.

00:07:50.590 --> 00:07:53.720
To disrupt their leadership
before they could launch what

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:55.730
was presumed to be
following attacks.

00:07:55.730 --> 00:08:00.040
And so the war never really
reckoned with what Afghanistan

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:02.330
after the invasion would be

00:08:02.330 --> 00:08:04.970
because it was really
being conceived within two

00:08:04.970 --> 00:08:09.370
or three weeks of the shock
of the September 11th attacks.

00:08:09.370 --> 00:08:12.600
So in the subsequent period
after the Taliban fell

00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:17.000
at the end of 2001 and al-Qaeda
largely escaped Afghanistan

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.860
and migrated into Pakistan, the
war since then has been plagued

00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:26.110
by recurring arguments and
confusion over war aims.

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:27.410
I want to talk about that.

00:08:27.410 --> 00:08:33.070
Second thing that has really
been repetitive although it was

00:08:33.070 --> 00:08:37.620
confined to the period
when Hamid Karzai was

00:08:37.620 --> 00:08:42.930
in office was the failure to
consolidate a relationship

00:08:42.930 --> 00:08:45.840
with Karzai that would
serve American interests

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:48.550
in the transition to
a post Karzai world.

00:08:48.550 --> 00:08:52.020
We, we really lost our
relationship with Karzai and,

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:53.750
and our investments

00:08:53.750 --> 00:08:56.960
in democratic Afghan
politics also faltered,

00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:00.070
not only because of our
conductor or decision making.

00:09:00.070 --> 00:09:02.900
Afghans had a lot to do with
that too, but I think the,

00:09:02.900 --> 00:09:04.860
the story of the failure
of the relationship

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:06.920
with Harmon Karzai is
particularly interesting

00:09:06.920 --> 00:09:10.570
because it goes to the
big problem of Pakistan.

00:09:10.570 --> 00:09:13.790
The biggest puzzle I think
for a lot of people who served

00:09:13.790 --> 00:09:15.440
in the war and certainly
for a lot

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:19.500
of Afghans throughout the war
after 2001 and particularly

00:09:19.500 --> 00:09:24.110
when the Taliban started to
revive around 2004 or 2005

00:09:24.110 --> 00:09:27.680
in seriousness, was
why the United States

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:31.270
and NATO were willing
to accept the sanctuary

00:09:31.270 --> 00:09:33.950
and the support the
Taliban enjoyed,

00:09:33.950 --> 00:09:38.220
still enjoy across the
border in Pakistan even

00:09:38.220 --> 00:09:40.900
when Pakistan was receiving
hundreds of millions of dollars

00:09:40.900 --> 00:09:45.340
in U.S. aid and even
after it became obvious

00:09:45.340 --> 00:09:49.250
that the Taliban were
prevailing or certainly working

00:09:49.250 --> 00:09:51.990
up a pretty bloody
stalemate in Afghanistan

00:09:51.990 --> 00:09:55.350
because of the sanctuary
and the training and the aid

00:09:55.350 --> 00:09:58.620
that they enjoyed
covertly from Pakistan

00:09:58.620 --> 00:10:01.080
and from Pakistan's principle
intelligence service,

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:03.040
Interviews Intelligence or ISI.

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:06.870
The title of the book
Directorate S refers

00:10:06.870 --> 00:10:08.650
to the covert action arm.

00:10:08.650 --> 00:10:10.770
It's what the American's
sometimes called the,

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:13.090
the covert action arm of ISI,

00:10:13.090 --> 00:10:15.480
the Pakistanian Intelligence
Service that works with groups

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:20.110
like the Taliban related
groups in Cashmere to carry

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:21.990
out what Pakistan's army sees

00:10:21.990 --> 00:10:24.290
as its foreign policy
interests in the region.

00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:26.520
Of course the American's
knew all about ISI

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:27.820
because we had collaborated

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:30.570
with them during the 1980's
during the Soviet Union along

00:10:30.570 --> 00:10:33.500
with Saudi intelligence, we
pumped billions of dollars

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:37.220
into the Alphagan rebel
force based in Pakistan.

00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:39.240
That also prevailed
of the Soviet Union

00:10:39.240 --> 00:10:44.130
because it enjoyed this physical
sanctuary and covert aid

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:46.090
that we participated in.

00:10:46.090 --> 00:10:49.660
So why, why did we fail
to recognize ISI's revival

00:10:49.660 --> 00:10:52.650
and why did it turn out
to be so flummoxing?

00:10:52.650 --> 00:10:54.680
Something we can talk about.

00:10:54.680 --> 00:10:57.720
Alright so that's the real
principle narrative of the book.

00:10:57.720 --> 00:11:01.530
It opens -- Ghost Wars closes
on the eve of the 9 11 attacks.

00:11:01.530 --> 00:11:03.840
It's about the, the history

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:06.640
between the Soviet
invasion and 9 11.

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:10.560
And this is intended
as a second volume

00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:13.140
of Ghost Wars although its kind
o f a funny thing as a writer

00:11:13.140 --> 00:11:15.800
to write a second volume of
a book that wasn't intended

00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:18.850
to be the first of two, but
that's kind of what this is.

00:11:18.850 --> 00:11:22.420
And it ends where Ghost Wars
stops quite deliberately

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:24.580
and comes forward to
something like the present day

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:28.260
and has many of the same
reporting and narrative,

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:31.790
story-telling strategies
as the first volume.

00:11:31.790 --> 00:11:36.540
Alright so I promised to go over
this, this subject of war aims.

00:11:36.540 --> 00:11:39.060
One of the things-- you know
I was kind of a beat reporter

00:11:39.060 --> 00:11:43.210
on the war after 9 11 because
I had accidental expertise

00:11:43.210 --> 00:11:44.510
about Afghanistan.

00:11:44.510 --> 00:11:46.190
I had been assigned out
there by the Washington Post

00:11:46.190 --> 00:11:47.490
as a foreign correspondent.

00:11:47.490 --> 00:11:48.790
I had covered the war

00:11:48.790 --> 00:11:51.630
on the ground long before 9 11
before anyone was really very

00:11:51.630 --> 00:11:52.930
interested in it.

00:11:52.930 --> 00:11:55.520
But it was a -- I, I became kind

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:58.000
of a professional obsession
and a great interest.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.880
I loved the landscape and the
people that I met in Afghanistan

00:12:01.880 --> 00:12:04.660
and Pakistan and I found
the war and the structure

00:12:04.660 --> 00:12:09.050
of covert action that shaped
so much misery and radicalism

00:12:09.050 --> 00:12:11.000
in the region to be
an important subject

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:12.650
and one that fascinated me.

00:12:12.650 --> 00:12:16.870
But after 9 11 because of that
background I kept going back

00:12:16.870 --> 00:12:18.190
to the region Pakistan

00:12:18.190 --> 00:12:20.750
and Afghanistan doing
a lot of reporting.

00:12:20.750 --> 00:12:22.490
And I, and I also was a creature

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:25.480
of Washington covering the
National Security bureaucracy

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:27.990
and interagency debates
about U.S. Policy

00:12:27.990 --> 00:12:30.680
in Afghanistan and in the war.

00:12:30.680 --> 00:12:33.030
And so when I went
back to do the research

00:12:33.030 --> 00:12:36.910
to really excavate the history
of decision making in Washington

00:12:36.910 --> 00:12:41.410
about policy in the Afghan war
and policy toward Pakistan,

00:12:41.410 --> 00:12:44.510
I was surprised and a
little bit disheartened

00:12:44.510 --> 00:12:49.810
to encounter what I didn't
fully appreciate as a kind

00:12:49.810 --> 00:12:54.050
of beat reporter which is the
repetitive nature of the debates

00:12:54.050 --> 00:12:58.310
about why are we in Afghanistan
and who is our enemy?

00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:01.420
The Busch administration
through several phases,

00:13:01.420 --> 00:13:04.300
right up until the
last days and months

00:13:04.300 --> 00:13:06.540
of the Bush administration
convened

00:13:06.540 --> 00:13:08.420
in a classified conference room

00:13:08.420 --> 00:13:10.340
in the Eisenhower
Executive Office Building

00:13:10.340 --> 00:13:11.720
which is next door
to the White House.

00:13:11.720 --> 00:13:13.420
If you're walking by the
White House it's over there

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:16.820
to the right, that very
ornate looking building,

00:13:16.820 --> 00:13:18.120
on the fourth floor.

00:13:18.120 --> 00:13:20.410
And they would typically
spend a whole day wrestling

00:13:20.410 --> 00:13:22.870
over what direction to
take in Afghanistan.

00:13:22.870 --> 00:13:25.210
They'd have the intelligence
analyst come in, in the morning

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:26.590
and try to brief the facts.

00:13:26.590 --> 00:13:27.980
This is what the map looks like.

00:13:27.980 --> 00:13:32.410
These are, these are the,
the principle ethnic groups.

00:13:32.410 --> 00:13:34.350
Here are the principle factions.

00:13:34.350 --> 00:13:36.790
And then they would leave and
the policy makers would debate.

00:13:36.790 --> 00:13:39.460
And they would get to
these basic questions.

00:13:39.460 --> 00:13:42.580
Are the Taliban our enemy?

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:45.570
There were no Afghans'
on the planes on 9 11.

00:13:45.570 --> 00:13:49.420
So far known the Afghan
Taliban have never carried

00:13:49.420 --> 00:13:52.740
out a terrorist attack
as an organization

00:13:52.740 --> 00:13:56.630
against the United States
in the U.S. or in Europe.

00:13:56.630 --> 00:14:00.470
They were attacked initially
because they were correctly seen

00:14:00.470 --> 00:14:03.510
as providing sanctuary
to al-Qaeda.

00:14:03.510 --> 00:14:08.110
Their alliance with al-Qaeda
was always uneasy and debatable.

00:14:08.110 --> 00:14:12.280
And so in these policy decisions
starting in 2006 repeating

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:18.530
in 2008 and in 209 and in 2012
and in 2014, the best minds

00:14:18.530 --> 00:14:19.830
in the U.S. government.

00:14:19.830 --> 00:14:24.020
The best informed south Asia
policy makers would return

00:14:24.020 --> 00:14:26.810
to this conference room,
write up white papers try

00:14:26.810 --> 00:14:29.170
to develop recommendations
to the president.

00:14:29.170 --> 00:14:32.660
And one of the questions they
kept returning too is what are

00:14:32.660 --> 00:14:35.620
our vital interests
in Afghanistan

00:14:35.620 --> 00:14:38.910
that justify the kinds of
sacrifices that we ask young men

00:14:38.910 --> 00:14:42.220
and women in uniform
to make over there?

00:14:42.220 --> 00:14:46.830
And an example would be in
2009 during the first year

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:50.140
of the Obama administration
a new group came in went back

00:14:50.140 --> 00:14:52.450
to the same conference room,
picked up the white papers

00:14:52.450 --> 00:14:55.210
that the Bush administration
had left behind went back

00:14:55.210 --> 00:14:56.510
to this question.

00:14:56.510 --> 00:14:58.200
And they were cleared eyed about
what the question should be.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:14:59.790
As taxpayers you would want them

00:14:59.790 --> 00:15:03.600
to be asking what vital
interests really justify this

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:05.710
kind of military sacrifice?

00:15:05.710 --> 00:15:08.820
And they worked on that
for weeks and months.

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:11.450
And in the end they
identified two.

00:15:11.450 --> 00:15:15.120
One was al-Qaeda which
was still carrying

00:15:15.120 --> 00:15:19.050
out international attacks
from the, from the region

00:15:19.050 --> 00:15:21.160
against the United States,

00:15:21.160 --> 00:15:24.120
attempting attacks inside
the United States also

00:15:24.120 --> 00:15:26.670
in Europe and elsewhere.

00:15:26.670 --> 00:15:32.190
And the second was the security
of Pakistani's nuclear weapons

00:15:32.190 --> 00:15:34.600
because Pakistan has
about 100 nuclear weapons.

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:36.410
It has a lot of radical
groups on its soil.

00:15:36.410 --> 00:15:40.080
And the nightmare scenario would
be if somehow Pakistan became

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:42.220
so destabilized that
these weapons fell

00:15:42.220 --> 00:15:45.510
into the wrong hands.

00:15:45.510 --> 00:15:48.910
But consider this contradiction,
the first of half a dozen

00:15:48.910 --> 00:15:52.990
that we can review over
the next 20 minutes.

00:15:52.990 --> 00:15:56.960
Neither al-Qaeda nor
Pakistani's nuclear weapons were

00:15:56.960 --> 00:15:59.430
in Afghanistan in 2009,
where the president was

00:15:59.430 --> 00:16:02.300
about to send 100,000 troops.

00:16:02.300 --> 00:16:03.600
So if the vital interests are

00:16:03.600 --> 00:16:07.860
in Pakistan why are we fighting
a war next door in Afghanistan?

00:16:07.860 --> 00:16:09.650
The, the president's
advisors were smart enough

00:16:09.650 --> 00:16:11.030
to understand this
contradiction,

00:16:11.030 --> 00:16:12.330
so they wrestled with it.

00:16:12.330 --> 00:16:16.120
And they said "Well it's
sort of an indirect reason

00:16:16.120 --> 00:16:18.870
because if Afghanistan
falls apart,

00:16:18.870 --> 00:16:22.730
then al-Qaeda will come
back into Afghanistan

00:16:22.730 --> 00:16:27.010
and that may also
destabilize Pakistan.

00:16:27.010 --> 00:16:30.330
So we've got to shore up
this neighbor in order

00:16:30.330 --> 00:16:33.880
to pursue the vital
interests that are next door."

00:16:33.880 --> 00:16:35.180
I don't know.

00:16:35.180 --> 00:16:37.600
I mean as a parent sending
a child into harm's way,

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:42.880
that feels a little bit indirect
to me as a, as a, as a war aim.

00:16:42.880 --> 00:16:45.350
Well the other war aim then
that might justify this sort

00:16:45.350 --> 00:16:48.330
of sacrifice is you are
going to fight the Taliban.

00:16:48.330 --> 00:16:49.900
You're going to prevent
the Taliban

00:16:49.900 --> 00:16:54.660
from consolidating the momentum
which by 2009 it had quite a lot

00:16:54.660 --> 00:16:57.900
of on the ground in Afghanistan.

00:16:57.900 --> 00:17:01.100
But the policy makers
including --

00:17:01.100 --> 00:17:04.100
particularly during the early
Obama years were really divided

00:17:04.100 --> 00:17:06.480
about whether the Taliban
should be understood as an enemy

00:17:06.480 --> 00:17:09.030
of the United States partly
for the reasons I described.

00:17:09.030 --> 00:17:10.660
They're indigenous
to Afghanistan.

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:12.910
It was pointed out
in these debates.

00:17:12.910 --> 00:17:14.710
They are part of the
fabric of southern

00:17:14.710 --> 00:17:16.490
and eastern Afghanistan.

00:17:16.490 --> 00:17:18.590
They have, they have
not declared war

00:17:18.590 --> 00:17:19.890
against the Unites States.

00:17:19.890 --> 00:17:21.190
They're abhorrent.

00:17:21.190 --> 00:17:22.490
Their ideas are abhorrent.

00:17:22.490 --> 00:17:25.320
We certainly don't want
them to take power.

00:17:25.320 --> 00:17:27.760
But are they an enemy?

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:31.180
The truth was that President
Obama did not believe the United

00:17:31.180 --> 00:17:34.540
States should attempt to fight a
forever war against the Taliban

00:17:34.540 --> 00:17:36.830
and that there was
neither the political clock

00:17:36.830 --> 00:17:40.780
in the Unites States nor the
resources nor the prospect

00:17:40.780 --> 00:17:44.040
of military victory to
justify such an endeavor.

00:17:44.040 --> 00:17:46.040
But his generals had
sold him on the idea

00:17:46.040 --> 00:17:48.130
of a counter insurgency
war that could succeed

00:17:48.130 --> 00:17:50.580
in Afghanistan the way it was
perceived to have succeeded

00:17:50.580 --> 00:17:55.210
in Bagdad after the
surge at there in 2006.

00:17:55.210 --> 00:17:57.570
And so the president
was reluctant

00:17:57.570 --> 00:18:00.730
to at least initially --

00:18:00.730 --> 00:18:04.200
that's a funnier
conversation than Afghanistan.

