Anyway there's a scene where
the president basically makes it

00:18:27.420 --> 00:18:29.810
known through his White House
aid's that he doesn't want

00:18:29.810 --> 00:18:32.070
to fight this forever
war against the Taliban,

00:18:32.070 --> 00:18:34.430
so his aids go into this
secure conference room

00:18:34.430 --> 00:18:36.340
or the situation room
one day and they say

00:18:36.340 --> 00:18:39.600
"Have we ever really
said that it was our aim

00:18:39.600 --> 00:18:41.470
to defeat the Taliban?"

00:18:41.470 --> 00:18:44.080
And the Pentagon
representatives are appalled.

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:46.620
And the next day they come
back with a big PowerPoint deck

00:18:46.620 --> 00:18:48.410
that shows all the
different statements

00:18:48.410 --> 00:18:51.150
that American presidents
and senators have made

00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:54.270
about our intention to
vanquish the Taliban

00:18:54.270 --> 00:18:55.570
from the face of the earth.

00:18:55.570 --> 00:18:56.870
They say, "You may not
want to fight this war,

00:18:56.870 --> 00:18:58.750
but you've said you've
signed up for it."

00:18:58.750 --> 00:19:02.400
And, and so yes we have declared
our interest in defeating it.

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:06.300
But when the troop surge
announcements were made,

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:09.320
if you parsed that language,
he's very careful not to declare

00:19:09.320 --> 00:19:12.380
that we intend to defeat the
Taliban on the battlefield.

00:19:12.380 --> 00:19:15.280
The, the war aim was to reduce

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:18.750
or reverse the Taliban's
momentum to create space

00:19:18.750 --> 00:19:23.710
for Afghan forces to take the
lead and, and essentially kind

00:19:23.710 --> 00:19:26.070
of Vietnmization
of the Afghan war.

00:19:26.070 --> 00:19:27.370
And that was achieved.

00:19:27.370 --> 00:19:29.350
It still has been
achieved today.

00:19:29.350 --> 00:19:33.200
The war is a stalemate now,
just as it was in 2007.

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:36.240
One of the episodes the book
described repeatedly is this --

00:19:36.240 --> 00:19:38.310
these very popular
classified maps

00:19:38.310 --> 00:19:41.110
that the CIA would produce
called the District Assessments

00:19:41.110 --> 00:19:44.050
which were derived from a
similar mapping exercise carried

00:19:44.050 --> 00:19:45.620
out during the Vietnam War.

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:47.780
They would take all
of approximately --

00:19:47.780 --> 00:19:50.510
Afghanistan spans
approximately 400 districts,

00:19:50.510 --> 00:19:53.740
administrative districts
and color code them based

00:19:53.740 --> 00:19:57.990
on the latest intelligence and
open information as to whether

00:19:57.990 --> 00:19:59.870
or not they're controlled
by the Taliban or controlled

00:19:59.870 --> 00:20:02.170
by the Afghan government,
contested or locally controlled

00:20:02.170 --> 00:20:04.440
by some other war lord.

00:20:04.440 --> 00:20:07.400
And essentially they would
come in and unfurl these maps.

00:20:07.400 --> 00:20:09.820
Everyone would poor over them
looking for subtle changes.

00:20:09.820 --> 00:20:13.600
The reality is they haven't
changed color in 10 years.

00:20:13.600 --> 00:20:16.840
They're made every six months
and things move around.

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:19.050
And green appears here
and red appears there.

00:20:19.050 --> 00:20:20.770
The wars stalemated
and it's stalemated

00:20:20.770 --> 00:20:25.570
because the Taliban have no air
force and they have no answer

00:20:25.570 --> 00:20:30.080
for the U.S. Air Force, so they
can't mask very successfully.

00:20:30.080 --> 00:20:33.350
But also neither
the NATO led troops

00:20:33.350 --> 00:20:38.170
which after peak numbered
150,000 in Afghanistan in 2010.

00:20:38.170 --> 00:20:43.590
Nor the Afghan forces after we
reduced our presence has had an

00:20:43.590 --> 00:20:47.100
answer for the sanctuary in
Pakistan for the role of ISI

00:20:47.100 --> 00:20:48.790
and supporting the
Taliban in the war

00:20:48.790 --> 00:20:52.430
or for the Taliban's coercive
control of quite a lot

00:20:52.430 --> 00:20:57.070
of rural districts particularly
in the south and east.

00:20:57.070 --> 00:20:58.970
Loosing Hamid Karzai.

00:20:58.970 --> 00:21:01.720
Again as a beat reporter
I, I covered Hamid Karzai

00:21:01.720 --> 00:21:03.180
for a long time over the years.

00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:04.600
I've interviewed him
a couple of times

00:21:04.600 --> 00:21:06.680
and watched him in
press conferences.

00:21:06.680 --> 00:21:09.560
He's a fascinating figure
and certainly was as,

00:21:09.560 --> 00:21:11.540
as he became the
unexpected president

00:21:11.540 --> 00:21:14.230
of Afghanistan after 2001.

00:21:14.230 --> 00:21:18.150
And I thought I understood
him reasonably well.

00:21:18.150 --> 00:21:20.790
I was aware certainly by the
time I was working on this book

00:21:20.790 --> 00:21:22.230
that he had gained a reputation

00:21:22.230 --> 00:21:25.280
as being this very
unstable individual

00:21:25.280 --> 00:21:28.900
who was constantly going off and
attacking the United States and,

00:21:28.900 --> 00:21:31.480
and kind of involved
in conspiracy theories

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:33.070
and that sort of thing.

00:21:33.070 --> 00:21:36.080
Again I was surprised when
I kind of excavated as many

00:21:36.080 --> 00:21:38.980
of the private conversations
that he had with his own cabinet

00:21:38.980 --> 00:21:42.600
or with the American's
that he was very consistent

00:21:42.600 --> 00:21:44.510
over the years about one thing.

00:21:44.510 --> 00:21:48.270
Every time an American would
come to visit him he would say,

00:21:48.270 --> 00:21:50.600
"You're not doing enough to
put pressure on Pakistan.

00:21:50.600 --> 00:21:53.190
These sanctuaries
are unacceptable.

00:21:53.190 --> 00:21:55.410
And ISI's interference
in the war is going

00:21:55.410 --> 00:21:56.980
to make the war unwinnable.

00:21:56.980 --> 00:21:58.350
Why are you not doing this?

00:21:58.350 --> 00:22:00.450
Why are you not -- why
are you treating them

00:22:00.450 --> 00:22:02.710
as if this isn't going on?"

00:22:02.710 --> 00:22:04.380
And the American's
at first would say,

00:22:04.380 --> 00:22:07.210
"Well yeah I don't think you
understand President Musharraf

00:22:07.210 --> 00:22:09.940
who is seen as a reliable
ally of the United States.

00:22:09.940 --> 00:22:11.240
He's a friend.

00:22:11.240 --> 00:22:12.540
He's trying to do his best."

00:22:12.540 --> 00:22:15.150
Later the American's agreed
that ISI was a problem

00:22:15.150 --> 00:22:17.520
but they felt they couldn't put
too much pressure on Pakistan

00:22:17.520 --> 00:22:20.030
because after all Pakistan
itself was convulsed

00:22:20.030 --> 00:22:23.690
by internal violence caused
in part by the migration

00:22:23.690 --> 00:22:25.770
of al-Qaeda into Pakistan.

00:22:25.770 --> 00:22:29.010
They had the worst domestic
terrorism they ever experienced

00:22:29.010 --> 00:22:31.280
in 2009, 2010.

00:22:31.280 --> 00:22:32.580
And if a vital interest

00:22:32.580 --> 00:22:34.420
of the United States was
preventing Pakistan's nuclear

00:22:34.420 --> 00:22:35.960
weapons from getting
into the wrong hands,

00:22:35.960 --> 00:22:37.410
you couldn't very well and go in

00:22:37.410 --> 00:22:40.790
and exacerbate the
almost civil war

00:22:40.790 --> 00:22:43.310
that Pakistan was
experiencing at that point.

00:22:43.310 --> 00:22:46.190
Nonetheless, we kept
confusing Karzai by kind

00:22:46.190 --> 00:22:48.270
of fluffing off his question.

00:22:48.270 --> 00:22:51.100
In the summer of 2008
then candidate Obama flew

00:22:51.100 --> 00:22:54.770
into Afghanistan on a
campaign visit and he went

00:22:54.770 --> 00:22:56.320
to meet Karzai and his cabinet.

00:22:56.320 --> 00:22:58.420
And this cabinet
really they all didn't

00:22:58.420 --> 00:22:59.720
like each other very much.

00:22:59.720 --> 00:23:01.690
They rarely cooperated on much,

00:23:01.690 --> 00:23:03.660
but they all got together
before the meeting and said,

00:23:03.660 --> 00:23:07.980
"Let's agree to emphasize,
to possible President Obama

00:23:07.980 --> 00:23:09.770
that it's all about ISI.

00:23:09.770 --> 00:23:11.180
It's all about Pakistan."

00:23:11.180 --> 00:23:12.920
So when each of them
went around the table

00:23:12.920 --> 00:23:15.760
and said something they all
said, "You really have to focus

00:23:15.760 --> 00:23:17.770
on this problem because
the sanctuary is going

00:23:17.770 --> 00:23:20.030
to make the war unwinnable."

00:23:20.030 --> 00:23:22.990
And when the United States
didn't do anything about it,

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:26.380
worse, when the United States
made it clear to Karzai

00:23:26.380 --> 00:23:28.480
that it thought that maybe
Pakistan was actually more

00:23:28.480 --> 00:23:31.590
important to the United
States than Afghanistan,

00:23:31.590 --> 00:23:33.920
he understandably
became deeply confused.

00:23:33.920 --> 00:23:35.220
There's a scene in the book

00:23:35.220 --> 00:23:38.230
where Vice-President
Joe Biden goes out early

00:23:38.230 --> 00:23:41.190
on in the Obama Administration
to meet with Karzai.

00:23:41.190 --> 00:23:43.780
The Obama Administration
came in and a lot

00:23:43.780 --> 00:23:46.460
of the administrations come
no matter which party it is

00:23:46.460 --> 00:23:49.800
and they think whatever the
last guys did was exactly wrong

00:23:49.800 --> 00:23:51.390
so we're going to
do the opposite.

00:23:51.390 --> 00:23:53.340
And one of the syndromes
and this case was

00:23:53.340 --> 00:23:55.390
that the Obama folks thought

00:23:55.390 --> 00:23:57.980
that the Busch administration
particularly President Bush

00:23:57.980 --> 00:23:59.890
personally had coddled Karzai,

00:23:59.890 --> 00:24:02.490
had spent too much
time holding his hand.

00:24:02.490 --> 00:24:04.910
Had, had accommodated
too much corruption,

00:24:04.910 --> 00:24:08.290
too much drug dealing and it
was time to get tough on him.

00:24:08.290 --> 00:24:11.040
So Biden was sent out to deliver
this message, you know the,

00:24:11.040 --> 00:24:14.100
the era of the friendly
video conference is over.

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:18.100
You, you got to clean up your
act and you can't expect us

00:24:18.100 --> 00:24:21.000
to accommodate you the way
the last administration did.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:23.520
So he's goes into this
private meeting with Karzai.

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:26.120
Karzai starts the
meeting by saying,

00:24:26.120 --> 00:24:27.750
"You know Mr. Vice-President,
you really need

00:24:27.750 --> 00:24:29.050
to do more about Pakistan.

00:24:29.050 --> 00:24:31.310
You really need to
do more about ISI."

00:24:31.310 --> 00:24:34.320
And Biden replies,
"Mr. President,

00:24:34.320 --> 00:24:36.790
Pakistan is 50 times
more important

00:24:36.790 --> 00:24:39.690
to the United States
than Afghanistan."

00:24:39.690 --> 00:24:43.990
So maybe not the most diplomatic
way to put pressure on Karzai.

00:24:43.990 --> 00:24:48.230
But you know in a lot of
south Asia and certainly a lot

00:24:48.230 --> 00:24:50.500
of similar parts of the
world, it's common to sink

00:24:50.500 --> 00:24:51.800
into conspiracy thinking.

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:55.080
And the way it wet for Karzai
was when he looked at the fact

00:24:55.080 --> 00:24:57.670
that the United States wasn't
putting any pressure on Pakistan

00:24:57.670 --> 00:24:59.980
and that Pakistan
was by the admission

00:24:59.980 --> 00:25:03.320
of many American Generals
and intelligence officers,

00:25:03.320 --> 00:25:06.020
that's its role in
the war was critical.

00:25:06.020 --> 00:25:09.940
He began to think well the
United States must want Pakistan

00:25:09.940 --> 00:25:11.370
to be reviving the Taliban.

00:25:11.370 --> 00:25:14.930
He must want Pakistan to be
destabilizing Afghanistan.

00:25:14.930 --> 00:25:17.730
He must want the American -- the
American's must want this war

00:25:17.730 --> 00:25:20.670
to grind on so that they can
justify having a long-term

00:25:20.670 --> 00:25:23.350
military presence
in the country.

00:25:23.350 --> 00:25:25.790
This is the kind of
confusion that you can create.

00:25:25.790 --> 00:25:29.170
Now diplomat after diplomat,
general after general would go

00:25:29.170 --> 00:25:30.790
to Karzai and say,
"No Mr. President,

00:25:30.790 --> 00:25:32.500
there's no such conspiracy.

00:25:32.500 --> 00:25:35.810
We're just doing our best to
try to keep this war going

00:25:35.810 --> 00:25:37.110
in the right direction."

00:25:37.110 --> 00:25:39.490
But Karzai was absolutely
convinced that the American's

00:25:39.490 --> 00:25:43.380
after a certain point were
deliberately allowing ISI

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:45.800
to create this war so
that they could justify a

00:25:45.800 --> 00:25:47.340
long-term presence.

00:25:47.340 --> 00:25:50.630
At one point a guy named Jim
Dobbin's in 2013 he goes out

00:25:50.630 --> 00:25:53.760
