the ground, and particularly

00:26:41.690 --> 00:26:45.080
after the United States launched
this counter-insurgency campaign

00:26:45.080 --> 00:26:51.270
in southern Afghanistan
in 2010, 2009, 2010, 2011.

00:26:51.270 --> 00:26:53.870
It was a war very distant war.

00:26:53.870 --> 00:26:57.500
Didn't get quite all of the
attention the reality of it.

00:26:57.500 --> 00:26:58.930
I don't think quite
soaked through.

00:26:58.930 --> 00:27:03.040
It was a volunteer army fighting
in very difficult terrain.

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:04.580
But it was a product of a kind

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:07.490
of faith encounter
insurgency expeditionary

00:27:07.490 --> 00:27:08.960
counter insurgency.

00:27:08.960 --> 00:27:12.300
As I mentioned followed out of
the perceived success in Bagdad.

00:27:12.300 --> 00:27:15.870
And if you were in town, in
national security circles

00:27:15.870 --> 00:27:19.820
in Washington, circa 2009
2010 it was like a bubble.

00:27:19.820 --> 00:27:23.620
It was like a Bit coin or
some other kind of sense,

00:27:23.620 --> 00:27:26.650
self reinforcing sense that
his idea is going to solve it.

00:27:26.650 --> 00:27:27.950
We're going to go
out there we're going

00:27:27.950 --> 00:27:31.290
to run this counter insurgency
campaign, connecting people

00:27:31.290 --> 00:27:34.470
to their government,
walking through villages,

00:27:34.470 --> 00:27:36.650
fighting it out one
path at a time.

00:27:36.650 --> 00:27:39.080
And it turned out I
places like Kandahar

00:27:39.080 --> 00:27:41.130
to be a very violent war.

00:27:41.130 --> 00:27:44.070
And so I looked for a
way to tell the story

00:27:44.070 --> 00:27:47.470
through one unit's experience
in the heart of the campaign.

00:27:47.470 --> 00:27:51.390
And I chose the part of the
campaign that was fought in the

00:27:51.390 --> 00:27:55.790
so called green zone to
the, to the west of Kandahar

00:27:55.790 --> 00:27:58.450
which is the Taliban's
birth place significant city

00:27:58.450 --> 00:28:00.330
in the south of Afghanistan.

00:28:00.330 --> 00:28:03.100
It's called the green zone
because though it's desert,

00:28:03.100 --> 00:28:05.530
there's the Arghandab
river flows through it

00:28:05.530 --> 00:28:07.950
and irrigation is
made possible much

00:28:07.950 --> 00:28:10.120
of the year through this river.

00:28:10.120 --> 00:28:12.790
And the vegetation around
in this green zone is

00:28:12.790 --> 00:28:14.160
incredibly thick.

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:17.940
That's great orchards
with drying houses

00:28:17.940 --> 00:28:21.530
and berms almost worse
than Normandy in terms

00:28:21.530 --> 00:28:23.970
of terrain to try to fight in.

00:28:23.970 --> 00:28:28.910
And foliage that's almost jungle
like in the canopy it creates.

00:28:28.910 --> 00:28:32.110
10 foot marijuana plants
being a feature of this.

00:28:32.110 --> 00:28:33.710
Big marijuana farming industry.

00:28:33.710 --> 00:28:36.170
One of the jobs the American's
had was to go out and cut

00:28:36.170 --> 00:28:38.890
down these 10 foot plants
then set them on fire

00:28:38.890 --> 00:28:42.440
which was not always
objected to as duty.

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:48.000
But it was -- the Taliban had
been imbedding in this zone for,

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.350
for years and years
and they build an

00:28:49.350 --> 00:28:50.650
incredible infrastructure.

00:28:50.650 --> 00:28:53.650
And the, and the purpose of the
counter insurgency campaign was

00:28:53.650 --> 00:28:55.840
to go in and knock them
out once and for all.

00:28:55.840 --> 00:28:59.620
So I'll just read you
a little passage from,

00:28:59.620 --> 00:29:00.920
from that campaign.

00:29:00.920 --> 00:29:02.400
The flavor of it.

00:29:02.400 --> 00:29:05.630
"So the initial phase of
Colonel Art Kandarian's campaign

00:29:05.630 --> 00:29:07.400
in the green zone wasn't
that much different of that

00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:10.690
of the U.S. Army in the American
West during the 19th century.

00:29:10.690 --> 00:29:14.320
Build forts in Indian
country and poke around.

00:29:15.990 --> 00:29:19.680
Forward American units
detains suspected insurgents

00:29:19.680 --> 00:29:22.820
and used retinal scanners to log
them into classified data bases,

00:29:22.820 --> 00:29:25.330
but interrogations and human
intelligence collection

00:29:25.330 --> 00:29:28.960
in Kandahar that summer rarely
produced insights besides the

00:29:28.960 --> 00:29:32.000
known fact that many
Taliban fighters were from

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:35.500
or trained in Pakistan."

00:29:35.500 --> 00:29:37.660
So the platoons that I write

00:29:37.660 --> 00:29:41.290
about were former artillery
units that had been converted

00:29:41.290 --> 00:29:43.250
to infantry because
during this period

00:29:43.250 --> 00:29:45.960
of the war the United States
military was so stressed

00:29:45.960 --> 00:29:49.510
by the cascading consequences
of fighting hard in Iraq

00:29:49.510 --> 00:29:51.640
and Afghanistan at
the same time,

00:29:51.640 --> 00:29:53.680
that they were piecing
together task forces

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:55.100
out of different units.

00:29:55.100 --> 00:29:57.360
And they were asking
artillery men

00:29:57.360 --> 00:30:04.300
to fight close infantry patrol
wars with a lot of IED's

00:30:04.300 --> 00:30:06.880
and implanted explosives.

00:30:06.880 --> 00:30:09.150
And, and this is you know a lot

00:30:09.150 --> 00:30:13.230
of these artillery men had been
trained to fight with big guns

00:30:13.230 --> 00:30:15.140
on bases at a remote distance.

00:30:15.140 --> 00:30:19.030
They were engineers and
they weren't used to this.

00:30:19.030 --> 00:30:23.380
They -- so they would build
these outposts in the middle

00:30:23.380 --> 00:30:27.190
of the green zone, barely
being able to see five feet

00:30:27.190 --> 00:30:31.850
over the wall and then they
would go out and patrol on foot

00:30:31.850 --> 00:30:36.750
by contact, trying to just
draw the Taliban into contact.

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:39.090
"Platoons depended on their
most experienced sergeants

00:30:39.090 --> 00:30:40.390
to survive.

00:30:40.390 --> 00:30:43.190
Sergeant Josh Strickland had
served two tours in Iraq and one

00:30:43.190 --> 00:30:46.570
in Afghanistan before joining
third platoon a battery

00:30:46.570 --> 00:30:49.760
of the 1-320th the
artillery misfits.

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:52.810
During the first couple of weeks
of -- at combat outpost Noland,

00:30:52.810 --> 00:30:55.180
Strickland's patrol
could not walk 100 years

00:30:55.180 --> 00:30:57.440
without hitting an
IED or getting lit

00:30:57.440 --> 00:30:59.890
up by Taliban from
several sides.

00:30:59.890 --> 00:31:02.340
Listening to the enemy radio
talk they learned the enemy knew

00:31:02.340 --> 00:31:05.910
they were artillery
not infantry.

00:31:05.910 --> 00:31:09.190
In general, Strickland thought
the lowest ranking first time

00:31:09.190 --> 00:31:10.900
soldiers adjusted
to the stress better

00:31:10.900 --> 00:31:12.670
than the more experienced
artillery men

00:31:12.670 --> 00:31:14.300
because the rookies
had no expectations

00:31:14.300 --> 00:31:16.300
from prior deployments.

00:31:16.300 --> 00:31:18.840
Because of Strickland's
experience and uncanny ability

00:31:18.840 --> 00:31:21.810
to avoid IED's soldiers
continually asked him

00:31:21.810 --> 00:31:23.880
to walk point on their patrols.

00:31:23.880 --> 00:31:26.590
He chose to walk 10 to 15
feet ahead of everyone else

00:31:26.590 --> 00:31:29.650
so that he could carefully
identify the best route and so

00:31:29.650 --> 00:31:32.160
that if he did make a mistake
it would cost one life instead

00:31:32.160 --> 00:31:33.460
of several.

00:31:33.460 --> 00:31:35.050
He was ultimately
wounded and medivaced

00:31:35.050 --> 00:31:37.240
to Kandahar airfield four times.

00:31:37.240 --> 00:31:38.560
Each time as he recovered

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:40.560
in the hospital a doctor would
ask Strickland if he wanted

00:31:40.560 --> 00:31:42.250
to go back or go home.

00:31:42.250 --> 00:31:43.550
"What am I going to say?"

00:31:43.550 --> 00:31:44.850
he thought.

00:31:44.850 --> 00:31:46.150
He went back.

00:31:46.150 --> 00:31:47.450
Day after day they
shouldered their loads,

00:31:47.450 --> 00:31:49.280
stepped on presence patrols
and hoped for the best.

00:31:49.280 --> 00:31:51.900
They walked past villagers
near their outposts

00:31:51.900 --> 00:31:53.940
who were neither
helpful nor hostile.

00:31:53.940 --> 00:31:56.010
One elder near Strickland's
base kept a pigeon

00:31:56.010 --> 00:31:58.690
that he would let fly every
time a platoon departed,

00:31:58.690 --> 00:32:02.100
apparently to let the Taliban
know they were on the march.

00:32:02.100 --> 00:32:05.940
By July IED's and the escalating
casualties had rattled the most

00:32:05.940 --> 00:32:09.300
experienced infantry men.

00:32:09.300 --> 00:32:11.390
Every soldier carried
70 to 90 pounds

00:32:11.390 --> 00:32:13.050
of gear, water and ammunition.

00:32:13.050 --> 00:32:15.550
They patrolled at
night to avoid the sun.

00:32:15.550 --> 00:32:18.800
They drank water continually
to stave off dehydration.

00:32:18.800 --> 00:32:21.440
The IED's were so thick
around the bulldog encampment

00:32:21.440 --> 00:32:24.560
that they had to clear 100 years
at a time from the walls out.

00:32:24.560 --> 00:32:27.540
A lot of soldiers
struggled with the stress.

00:32:27.540 --> 00:32:31.130
The first platoon of the
1-320th started out with 19 men.

00:32:31.130 --> 00:32:33.940
After three patrols, they had 6.

00:32:33.940 --> 00:32:38.110
80%, 80% Bravo company's
personnel had

00:32:38.110 --> 00:32:40.320
to be replaced during
Strickland's tour

00:32:40.320 --> 00:32:43.060
because of combat
vets severed limbs,

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:45.950
concussions or other injuries."

00:32:45.950 --> 00:32:49.460
Now you think of those
percentages, I mean that sound

00:32:49.460 --> 00:32:52.470
like Battle of the Bulge.

00:32:52.470 --> 00:32:53.830
Wasn't, it -- wasn't present

00:32:53.830 --> 00:32:58.400
in American life
that part of the war.

00:32:58.400 --> 00:33:00.720
And one of the reasons
that I want to finish

00:33:00.720 --> 00:33:03.480
on the last theme I
want to touch on is

00:33:03.480 --> 00:33:08.520
because we really didn't
have a national debate

00:33:08.520 --> 00:33:10.740
about the war during the time

00:33:10.740 --> 00:33:14.860
that these sacrifices
were being sought.

00:33:14.860 --> 00:33:18.850
And we also failed to
reckon with the kind

00:33:18.850 --> 00:33:24.490
of political strategy that was
necessary given the history

00:33:24.490 --> 00:33:28.940
of wars of this kind to really
fashion any kind of exit

00:33:28.940 --> 00:33:31.930
from the war that
would be sustainable.

00:33:31.930 --> 00:33:34.660
One of the contradictions that
keeps recurring in history is

00:33:34.660 --> 00:33:36.950
that every general who
goes out to command.

00:33:36.950 --> 00:33:39.700
They command usually for a
year at a time, maybe two years

00:33:39.700 --> 00:33:43.360
at a time If there, if
they stay for a long while.

00:33:43.360 --> 00:33:47.410
Every general who goes out for
the American effort will say,

00:33:47.410 --> 00:33:51.000
"There is no military victory
possible against the Taliban.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:52.690
The only way this
war will end will be

00:33:52.690 --> 00:33:56.340
through political negotiations
and some kind of settlement."

00:33:56.340 --> 00:33:59.690
And yet again and again
military action is, is,

00:33:59.690 --> 00:34:03.060
is resourced ahead of
political strategy.

00:34:03.060 --> 00:34:07.190
And there is very little
effort of a serious kind made

00:34:07.190 --> 00:34:11.340
to bring the regional
powers, the great powers,

00:34:11.340 --> 00:34:12.850
the international system

00:34:12.850 --> 00:34:15.190
into negotiation to
stabilize the war.

00:34:15.190 --> 00:34:19.990
The book recounts this very
interesting secret negotiation

00:34:19.990 --> 00:34:22.710
the Obama administration
carried out with the Taliban

00:34:22.710 --> 00:34:25.980
between 2010 and 2013.

00:34:25.980 --> 00:34:27.330
It failed for a bunch
of reasons.

00:34:27.330 --> 00:34:31.010
The Trump administration is
trying something similar now.

00:34:31.010 --> 00:34:34.700
But it was always treated
as kind of a Hail Mary pass

00:34:34.700 --> 00:34:37.630
and never given the serious
international attention

00:34:37.630 --> 00:34:39.730
that for example
accompanied the efforts

00:34:39.730 --> 00:34:44.680
to cap Iran's nuclear program
with the P5 powers in Europe

00:34:44.680 --> 00:34:46.950
and everyone else involved.

00:34:46.950 --> 00:34:52.760
It's kind of a tragedy that we
keep repeating the same strategy

00:34:52.760 --> 00:34:54.060
again and again.

00:34:54.060 --> 00:34:56.180
And expecting a different
result, while asking

00:34:56.180 --> 00:34:59.250
for such large sacrifices
from our own soldiers

00:34:59.250 --> 00:35:00.840
and those of our allies.

00:35:00.840 --> 00:35:02.140
Thank you for listening.

